docs.abstract: Of the various book-to-film adaptations, these eight titles — including “If Beale Street Could Talk,” “The Sisters Brothers” and “The Hate U Give” — are worth reading before you watch.
docs.snippet: Of the various book-to-film adaptations, these eight titles — including “If Beale Street Could Talk,” “The Sisters Brothers” and “The Hate U Give” — are worth reading before you watch.
docs.lead_paragraph: Of the year’s non-franchise, non-superhero films, some of the most popular have been adapted from books, including “A Wrinkle in Time,” “Crazy Rich Asians” and the Netflix teenage romance “To All the Boys I’ve Loved Before.” One of the latest, “Bel Canto,” based on Ann Patchett’s novel and starring Julianne Moore and Ken Watanabe, was released on Sept. 14. Books, replete with emotional depth and rich character development, are ripe for onscreen interpretation, even if, for some readers, the end result isn’t always as rich in the visual telling. This fall brings a new batch of adaptations for readers to anticipate. Here are eight titles worth reading before you watch.
